column6: "Dieven" in Dutch means "thieves." Pathiramanal Island translates to "Midnight Sand Island." It's possible that the reference to "midnight" is associated with thieves, which could be one of the reasons behind this name.

column6: [DISAMBIGUATION] Map W37 features two places with somewhat similar names: [1] 'Tennepatnam', located between Canenoor (i.e. Kannur) and Talecheri (i.e. Thalassery); and [2] 'Trentpatnam', located more to the south, closer to Calichut (i.e. Kozhikode) and near a place called 'Coutta'. Likewise, Johann Hübner's work mentions two entries: 'Termapatan' and 'Tennepatnam'. The entry 'Termapatan' features closely after the entry Cananor and right before the entry Tellichery, which likely implies that 'Termapatan' was a place located between Kannur and Thalassery. Meanwhile, the entry 'Tennepatnam' features together with another place, 'Cota', and just before the entry for Calicut. From this comparison, it is reasonable to infer that: Hübner's entry of 'Termapatan' is the same as Map W37's 'Tennepatnam', whereas Hübner's entry of 'Tennepatnam' is actually the place that Map W37 labeled as 'Trentpatnam'.

column6: [DISAMBIGUATION] Map W37 features two places with somewhat similar names: [1] 'Tennepatnam', located between Canenoor (i.e. Kannur) and Talecheri (i.e. Thalassery); and [2] 'Trentpatnam', located more to the south, closer to Calichut (i.e. Kozhikode) and near a place called 'Coutta'. Likewise, Johann Hübner's work mentions two entries: 'Termapatan' and 'Tennepatnam'. The entry 'Termapatan' features closely after the entry Cananor and right before the entry Tellichery, which likely implies that 'Termapatan' was a place located between Kannur and Thalassery. Meanwhile, the entry 'Tennepatnam' features together with another place, 'Cota', and just before the entry for Calicut. From this comparison, it is reasonable to infer that: Hübner's entry of 'Termapatan' is the same as Map W37's 'Tennepatnam', whereas Hübner's entry of 'Tennepatnam' is actually the place that Map W37 labeled as 'Trentpatnam'.

column6: "Dieven" in Dutch means "thieves." Pathiramanal Island translates to "Midnight Sand Island." It's possible that the reference to "midnight" is associated with thieves, which could be one of the reasons behind this name.
